Deprived of his machines, the technician is still powerless against fire, algebra cannot save from the passage of time, etc. But Evola uses a specific phrase: "The sight of nature will still not speak to him, but it will mean to him less". St. Ignatius Brianchaninov mentions this

In one paragraph Dr. Julius Evola critiques scientific knowledge as failing to produce an ontological "self-transformation". Even if material progress exists, on the concrete plane one is still vulnerable to the elements if lost in the wild, is tortured by romantic passions, etc.

St. Brianchaninov says sights like a sunset at sea can produce an inspiration only in a man who undergoes purification in confession and prayer. A man who partakes in sin cannot read the Book of Nature and sees only death. Romans 1:20. The spiritually blind cannot witness nature.
